  "findings": [
    "Both models loaded to GPU 0 (RTX 3090, 24 GB): model_loader.load_model() resolves device=\"cuda:N\" to \"cuda\" (default device), so device_index=1 was not honoured. This is a known limitation in model_loader.py \u2014 fix requires passing device_map={\"\":device_index} or torch_dtype + device separately.",
    "GPU 0 VRAM post-load: Qwen3.5-0.8B=1459 MB, Gemma4-E4B-it delta not captured (same device, measurement taken on GPU 1). Total estimated ~10 GB on GPU 0.",
    "Dual-GPU concurrent test ran both models on GPU 0 concurrently (not truly separate GPUs). 93% parallelism efficiency observed \u2014 CUDA streams handled concurrent inference well.",
    "Qwen3.5-0.8B: 76.83 tok/s on GPU vs 15.76 tok/s on CPU = 4.88x speedup. p50=774ms, p95=830ms.",
    "Gemma4-E4B-it: 39.49 tok/s on GPU vs 1.41 tok/s on CPU = 28.01x speedup. High variance latency (p50=439ms, p95=1549ms) \u2014 likely due to variable token generation length.",
    "To truly use both GPUs independently, model_loader.py needs to pass device_map={\"\":device_index} to from_pretrained instead of calling model.cuda() after load."
  ],
  "action_items": [
    "Update model_loader.load_model() to support device_map for multi-GPU placement (future experiment).",
